    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>PPA method no longer works.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>While Oracle Java 6 and 7 are not supported for quite a while, they were still available for download on Oracle's website until recently.</p>\n<p>However, the binaries were removed about 10 days ago (?), so the Oracle Java (JDK) 6 and 7 installers available in the WebUpd8 Oracle Java PPA no longer work.</p>\n<p>Oracle Java 6 and 7 are now only available for those with an Oracle Support account (which is not free), so I can't support this for the PPA packages.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Source : <a href=\"http://www.webupd8.org/2017/06/why-oracle-java-7-and-6-installers-no.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">http://www.webupd8.org/2017/06/why-oracle-java-7-and-6-installers-no.html</a>\nDated : June 2017</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/index-jsp-138363.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Oracle's download page</a> says</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Updates for Java SE 7 released after April 2015, and updates for Java SE 6 released after April 2013 are only available to Oracle Customers through My Oracle Support (requires support login).</p>\n<p>Java SE Advanced offers users commercial features, access to critical bug fixes, security fixes, and general maintenance&quot;.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I had to download it from Oracle archives -\n<a href=\"http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/java-archive-downloads-javase7-521261.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/java-archive-downloads-javase7-521261.html</a></p>\n<p>You need an account for this though.</p>\n"
  }, {
